<l>Thei take which thing y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> Surgio<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g> sweares,<note place="margin">A thyng of necessitie proued to be phisicke, hauyng his confirma<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tion vpon the othe of a periured caitiffe Karne.</note>
<l>O that is cheare in <gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
<l>And makes the<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g> loke with dronken noules,</l>
<l>The Barde and Harper mellodie,<note place="margin">The Woodthiues loue mirth after meate.</note>
<l>the noble conquestes done,<note place="margin">A Barde and a Ri<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>mer is all one.</note>

<l>And eke in Rimes shewes forthe at large,<note place="margin">The Barde by his Rimes hath as great force emongst Wood<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>karne to perswade, as the elloquent oration of a learned Oratour emongest the ciuill people.</note>

<note place="margin">The pollicie of the Barde to encense the Rebelles to doe mischefe, by repeating then forfathers actes, O craftie Appostle as holy as a Deuill.</note>And more to stirre them vp,</l>

<note place="margin">Marke how apte and prone these theeues are to doe mischiefe, in whiche is verified the saiyng that is witten, like as the fa<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ther is, suche is the sonne, knaue father and knaue sonne, to the twentie genera<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tion.</note>As how by spoilyng honest menne,</l>
<note place="margin">A wicked man neuer wants ill counsell.</note>The Frier of his councells vile,</l>

<note place="margin">The Frier perswa<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>des the Rebels that it is an high worke of charitie, to kill loy<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>all Subiectes, which thyng they beleeue though neuer founde on scripture, O gho<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>stly Frier as inno<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>cent as Iudas.</note>Affirmyng that it is,</l>
<l>And for the doyng of the same,</l>
<note n="*" place="margin">Beholde the plaguy counsell of a pockie Frier, the very fruite of Papistrie.</note>he warrantes heauenlie blisse.</l>

<note n="*" place="margin">This flatteryng Frier promiseth to the Rebels euerla<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sting life, if they per<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>ceiuer in rebellyng a<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>gainst the (Queene.)</note>the white he tournes to blacke:</l>
<pb facs="tcp:14477:29"/>And through the pardons in his Male,</l>

<l>and Rebells waied haue:<note place="margin">The ende of the Fri<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ers oration, is the be<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ginnyng of rebellion, he is a sharpe spurre to make them gallop hedlong to all kinde of mischiefes, and last to the gallowes and deuill of hell.</note>
<l>doe take their onward waie.<note n="*" place="margin">The Karne go forth with the Friers bles<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>syng to spoyle loyall subiecttes, but looke what enseweth.</note>
<l>But loe whom traitours serue,<note place="margin">Whom the Frier doth blesse, them doth God curse, bringyng their wicked purpo<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ses to a wonderfull ende.</note>
<l>With strokes doe lode these filchyng theeues</l>
<l>The pray the rescude is,<note place="margin">The praie is recoue<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>red to the Rebels da<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>mage.</note>
<l>For heddes are swapt from shoulders quite,<note place="margin">Sweet<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
<l>And more to make their doyngs knowne,</l>

<note place="margin">As a notable Rebell had in his life tyme greater dignitie then many of like profes<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sion, so beyng dead, his head receiues a more stately place of exaltation.</note>to Dublin thei them beare:</l>
<l>Or if he were as rancke a knaue,</l>
<note place="margin">Suche Astronomers God sende vs enough daily.</note>Behidyng starres, as though he were,</l>

<note place="margin">Now God be than<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ked hedlesse Wood<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>karne are not to bee feared, fortune goeth beionde their expecta<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tions, which bryngeth Rebels with all their reuels to shame and dishonour.</note>Their bodies lackyng life,</l>
<note place="margin">The Frier mournes for the losse of his poore Woodkarne, he curseth as blacke as pitch their oppres<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sors.</note>The Frier seyng this,</l>
<l>And curseth to the pitte of hell,</l>

<note place="margin">The kindnesse of the Frier towardes the Rebelles after their death, by purchasyng their pardons, with booke, bell, and can<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>dell, whiche thyng ar<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tificially the knaue doth handell.</note>Yet for to quight them with,</l>
<l>For all the synnes that ere he did,</l>

<pb facs="tcp:14477:30"/>But thinke you that suche Apishetoies,<note n="*" place="margin">A notable question whiche demaundes, if pardones fro<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g> Rome, maie bryng damned soules from hell.</note>

<l>Yet hope that Friers giue,<note place="margin">Friers perswasions cause Rebelies still to perseuer in rebellion, O blinde fooles, to beleeue all that Pa<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>pisticall Monkishe momes tell you to bee Scripture, when in the ende they seeke your vtter destruction and desolation.</note>
<l>If that their soules should chaunce in hell,</l>

<l>Thus Friers are the cause,<note place="margin">The Friers in Ire<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>lande, are chiefest in<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>strumentes of Irishe disturbaunce, they are the onely spurre to pricke them onward to rebell against the Queene, procuryng the meanes of their vtter distruction, be<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>yng the hed welspring of all sinne and wic<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>kednesse.</note>

<note place="margin">Rebelles bewitched or deluded by sathan, measure not their owne estate by other mens harmes, or ca<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>lamities, but still marche forwarde in the pursute of sinne, till they come to like ende of destruction.</note>Yet that auaileth not,</l>

<note place="margin">As by obaiyng the Prince, there sprin<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>geth rest, peace, and tranquilitie, so, in dis<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>pleasing her Grace, groweth trouble, vex<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ation, confusion, and death.</note>In pleasyng whom is reste,</l>

<note n="*" place="margin">The Karne goe still on in their malice, gro<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>wyng from pettie fel<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>lonie to maine trea<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>son.</note>and marche in warlike wise:</l>
<l>Unto the feeld, with sworde and speare,</l>
<note n="*" place="margin">They boste of their manhood.</note>Thei bragge to fight it out,</l>

<note n="*" place="margin">They vowe, the En<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>glishe hostes destruc<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tion.</note>Thei sweare that all the Princ's freends, through bloudie sworde shall die.</l>
<note place="margin">The successe of reach<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>lesse enterprises.</note>Whereof doe rise a sodaine plague,</l>
<note place="margin">The celeritie of Sir Henry Sidney, to en<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>counter with the Re<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>belles.</note>Our valiaunt <hi>Sidney</hi> Lord,</l>
<note place="margin">The noble stomacke of the Captaines des<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>cribed.</note>And Captaines thei doe vowe,</l>
<l>Their hands should strike y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> warlike stroke,</l>

<note place="margin">The courage of the Souldiers liuely ex<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>pressed, who had ra<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ther then their liues be vpon the Iackets of these fif kyng and shippyng Rebelles.</note>The Souldiers doe reioyce,</l>

<pb facs="tcp:14477:31"/>And many Irelande Lords,<note n="*" place="margin">Recommendation of the good subiectes of Irelande, their fideli<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tie, loyaltie, and ser<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>uice to their Prince is described.</note>
<l>Protest through force of horse and speare,</l>
<l>the Iron hotte to beate.<note place="margin">The dai<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap>e is appointed, if wod<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>karne will abide it.</note>

<l>The messenger he trotteth forthe,<note place="margin">In this is manifestly proued how the Lord Deputie attempteth nothyng vnaduised<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ly, either in rearyng vp of warr or in put<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tyng it doune, where<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>by the Irishrie might finde any occasion of rebellion, or cause to rebell, for beyng come into the fielde in hostill araie, yet before he soundeth to the battaile, mercifully allureth them to submitte them selues to the Queenes good Grace, who refusing this offer, fallyng vpon them, showeth no mer<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>cie or compassion, whose eye doeth neither pitie them, nor yet his hande spare them, but like a most seuere warrier, executeth the function and office appertaing to warre</note>
<l>And worde for worde as he did speake,</l>
<l>Agen beholde the thyng<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">

<note place="margin">The marche of the Irishry and their no<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>table bragges beyng farre from their ene<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>mies, wherein they discouer openly their couragious dasterly hartes.</note>With three and three in ranckes be<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
<l>Thei set them selues moste liuely forthe,</l>
<note place="margin">The stately courage of the Rebelles, is sone put doune, at sight of our Princes hoste.</note>Doeth not the vewe of Princes hoste,</l>
<note place="margin">Feare a suppresser of the sturdiest Rebels harte.</note>What Rebell would not stande agaste,</l>

<note place="margin">The order of the I<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>rishe warre is plainly set out, who leauyng the order of battaile raye, beyng neare the combat, fall into a cluster, therein they suppose their saftie to consist<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap>, makyng a moste terrible noyse of criyng to terrifie (if it were possible) the whole hoste of En<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>glishe men.</note>Now warlicke raie thei leaue,</l>
<l>And Rebells whiche before did boaste,<note place="margin">Uauntyng Wood<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>karne doe first giue backe.</note>
<l>from shulders taken quight:<note place="margin">Under these <gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 word">
</gap> tytles, the valure of all our English Cap<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>taines are expressed.</note>
<l>When as his bill and tallentes bothe,</l>

<l>in Rebells bloud he hath.<note place="margin">O Souldiers of re<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>nowne shielde you from mischaunce, whiche doe in spight of Irishe karne, your Countries praise ad<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>uaunce.</note>
<l>Now goe the foes to wracke,<note place="margin">Woodkarne must needes sweate, for their labour is great.</note>
<l>And bagge Pipe then in steade of Trompe,<note n="*" place="margin">The piper seyng the Karne to haue the worste ende of the staffe, doe lull the I<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>rishe retreate.</note>

<l>Our valiant Captens will not cease,<note place="margin">Commendations worthie of right, to be long to our Englishe Captaines, who ne<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>uer shrincketh, but with greate valure and manhood tarieth the finall ende of the battaile.</note>
<l>And with their weapons meete for warre,</l>
<note place="margin">No daunger ought to be eschewed, nor labour refused, in the defendyng our prince and Countries cause.</note>This seekes by warlicke meanes,</l>
<l>And for his Prince and countries sake,</l>
<note place="margin">The gelousie of a Prince deuoureth like the flames of fire.</note>As how her iuste conceiued wrath,</l>
<note place="margin">The anger of a prince ceaseth not til he hath brought his purpose to perfection.</note>Till cuttyng sworde and pearcyng speare,</l>
<note place="margin">The Irishe Karnes hartes now more and more doe faint.</note>Now faint the ouglie beastes,</l>
<l>As thei are like to Bedlem folke,</l>
<note place="margin">Irishe Woodkarne had rather fli<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap> then fight, and good rea<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>son they haue so to do, for who would take blowes if he can shun them.</note>To flye thei dare assaie,</l>
<l>As for to stande to fight it out,</l>
<l>And now thei waile y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> thing which wrought</l>
<l>them this vnquiet reste.<note place="margin">Marke Traiters in the midst of battaile is no place to repent.</note>
<l>But will repentaunce serue?<note n="*" place="margin">A notable question that demaundes, if the repentaunce of <gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap> vile catrife, and re<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>bellious Wodkarne, maie satisfie the In<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>iuries committed a<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>gainst our Queene.</note>
<l>And twill be long who knowes it not,</l>
<l>And when he once beginnes,<note place="margin">A similitude of the Lyon.</note>
<l>He stintes not till he tournth his foes,</l>
<l>Euen so the Irishe Karne,<note place="margin">The Princes plea<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sure put in execution by Sir Henry Sid<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ney.</note>
<l>When gentlenesse preuaileth not,<note place="margin">Bygour is meetest where clemencie a<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>uaileth not.</note>
<l>Perforce doeth make them celebrate,<note place="margin">That whiche is doen by compulsion, is no go<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
<l>for Iustice commeth in:<note place="margin">Iustice and fortitude yeeldes Rebels their hire.</note>
<note place="margin">The Souldiers wrecke their anger and displeasure vpon the poore Irish karne without all pitie.</note>Thei prosecute the chase,</l>
<l>And with their weapons framde to warre,</l>
<note place="margin">O harde harted men that takes pitie of none.</note>the Karne thei ouerthrowe.</l>
<note place="margin">Woodkarne abides the brunt of fortune.</note>Here headlesse Knaues abide the bront,</l>
<note place="margin">Irishe Karne fight with their heeles with greater courage, then with their handes.</note>And for the sauyng of their liues,</l>
<note place="margin">The piper and his bagpipe laide bothe flatte on the grounde.</note>The Bagpipe cease to plaie,</l>
<l>And here a sorte of glibbed theeues,</l>
<note n="*" place="margin">The Woodkarnes legges must helpe them when handes will not serue them.</note>Now flye whose lucke is beste,</l>

<note place="margin">Uery good counsell giuen to the remnant of Woodkarne, war<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>nyng them how they doe attempt any thing preiudicall to the ho<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>nour of the Crowne.</note>Lament thy wofull state,</l>
<note place="margin">As the Lyon is fea<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>red, and reuerenced of all the beastes in the Forrest, so ought <gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap> King to be feared and loued of his sub<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>iectes within his Realme.</note>The Lyon for no mortall wight,</l>
<l>Els if you should repunge,<note place="margin">The rewarde of Re<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>bellion is death.</note>
<l>You might expecte at hands of his,</l>
<l>Let this a lesson bee,<note place="margin">A cauiat for Wood<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>karne.</note>
<l>To Macke, and O. to Rorie Ogge,</l>
<l>Let Brians fall suffice,<note place="margin">Good reason that the Asses calamity should make the Foxe to be ware.</note>
<l>vpon the Karne doe flye.<note place="margin">The corde that rebel<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>lion did binde, maie not be loused by any meanes, but by the ingen of death.</note>
<l>Bohbowe now crie the knaues,<note n="*" place="margin">The Irishe Karnes crie.</note>
<l>Here parte doe take the Bogges,<note place="margin">The remnaunt of the vnslaine Wodkarne, doe parte take the Bogges, and other some the Wood.</note>
<note place="margin">Irishe coltes are ta<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>med by the snaffie of warre.</note>Thus vauntyng foes are tamde,</l>
<note place="margin">Englishe men returne Conquerers</note>The victours doe retourne,</l>
<note place="margin">Sir Henry Sidney is worthely renowmd for prudence and magnanimitie.</note>Sir Henry is renowmde,</l>
<note place="margin">Peace commeth of warre.</note>Thus peace ensewes by warre,</l>
<note place="margin">A Godly praier that Irelande ought to vse.</note>God graunt the warres of Irishe sone,</l>

<seg rend="decorInit">A</seg>Fter that I had finished the first and se<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>conde parte of the Image of Irelande, and had there somewhat disclosed the nature and qualitie of the wantone Irishe wilde VVoodkarne, I thought it expedient for the vo<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>lumes augmentation, as more ampler by examples to proue the thinges therein co<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>tained, to put next in sequence, the picters and protractours of the moste notablest Rebelles in Irelande, (who as they are many) so doe thei aske sondrie opperations, if of eache seuerall one I should make relation. (And againe) musing in my mynde with whom I might encounter, as best beginne withall, hauing sondrie choyse to chose vpon, I supposed it a thing necessa<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>rie, and at this instant fittest to serue my turne, to laie the foundation of my attempt, <gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap> sure sub<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>stanciall corner stone, vpon Rory Ogge our next neighbour, at this present (a liuely Image <gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">

</gap> pat<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>terne of rebellion) who after many pagentes of treasons plaid, and notable offers of grace refused, beyng brought into greate miserie (by Sir Henry Sidney the Lorde Deputies daily instigation) and seyng hym self vtterly forsaken bothe of God

and man, at last moued through a desperate and condemned conscience, confessing his folly, manifesteth to the whole world, his croked nature, complaineth of his fatall destenie (and finally) as it were through a certaine coniecture, fore telleth of thynges that shortly shall happen hym. VVherefore behold in plaine protractour, a grose and corpulent man, lapped in a mantel ouerwhelmed with miserie, beyng in a VVood (an ill fauored Churle) standyng on a Hillocke enclosed with a shaking Bogge (his onely refuge in the tyme of trouble) vtteryng moste lamentably, with brynishe salte woluishe teares, his life as enseweth.
<note place="margin">Rorie Ogg sho<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>weth he<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap>e the Countie where<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>in he dwelleth, and his naturall inclination, whereunto he is addicted.</note> inhabitaunt of <hi>Leasse,</hi>
<l>I lead my life, in Boggs and thickets grene,</l>
<l>What mortall wight, my co<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>pere then hath seene,</l>
<l>Whiche of y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> lorde nor prince doeth stand in awe,</l>
<l>Nor passe not for, the rigour of the Lawe.</l>

<l>My harte is bent,<note place="margin">Marke where vnto this Re<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>belles harte is bent, (that is to saie) to all kind of mischiefe, sinne and wic<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>kednesse.</note> to eurie kinde of ill,</l>
<l>Whose outward deedes, doe well relate thesame</l>
<l>I loue the thyng, supporter of my will,</l>
<l>I spoile and burne, thereby t'encrease my fame,</l>
<l>Thus by suche actes, I gotten haue a name.</l>
<l>Euen traitour false, that neuer shall decaie,</l>
<l>Nor bee extinct, by any kinde of waie.</l>
<l>I vilaine vile, and craftie as the Foxe,</l>

<note n="*" place="margin">Rorie in accu<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sing hym self, is not to be iudged of other, for here he showeth that he is as craftie as a Foxe, an extortioner like the Wolfe, fal<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ser then a theef, and a traiter to the Queene, in whiche I beleue hym, though he neue<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap> swore for the matter.</note>Yea like the Wolfe, whiche doeth extortion vse,</l>
<l>I falser am, then theef that pickes the lockes,</l>
<l>In deulishe sorte, my self I so abuse:</l>
<l>(My noble Queene) for cheef I doe refuse,</l>
<l>Whose roiall name, doeth mo<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">

<l>What maie displease,<note place="margin">Rory Ogge go<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>yng forwarde in the settyng out of his dispositio<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g> telleth that he doeth all this kind of mischefe of set purpose a<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>gainst y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> queene, who notwith<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>standyng, laieth al the blame and falte vpon the Deuill.</note> her princly roiall grace,</l>
<l>(I like a theef) doe put the same in vre,</l>
<l>Her highnesse Lawes, I daiely doe deface,</l>
<pb facs="tcp:14477:37"/>And through y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> same, her heauie wrath procure:</l>
<l>Thus Sathan he, my sences doeth allure,</l>
<l>Who makes them thrall, to serue his appetite,</l>
<l>So that in nought, but synne I doe delight.</l>
<l>She would me good, if I would loyall bee,</l>
<l>But my ill happe, and crewell Destinie,</l>
<l>In parte or whole, that thyng forbiddeth me,</l>
<l>Though of the same, I stoode not erst in awe.</l>

<note n="*" place="margin">In this he ma<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>nifesteth the great goodnesse of the Queene, whose mercie is daily extended towardes those whiche are wil<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>lyng to yeelde to the obseruation of her statutes and lawes, but he in no wise maie yeeld ther<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>to, till by com<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>pulsion he bee constrained.</note>And forste perforce, God knowes what doth re<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>main</l>
<l>But cruel plages, for my desartes are iust,</l>
<l>Suche is the meede, whiche eurie Rebell gaine,</l>
<l>That doeth pursue, the chase of ragyng luste:</l>
<l>O carelesse Karne, O Rebell false to truste,</l>

<note n="*" place="margin">Rory Ogg be<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>yng compelde to acknowledge y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> great aucthority of the Prince, is therfore worthie of small goda<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>mercie.</note>O Rorie Ogge, thrice cursed maie I be,</l>
<l>Who mou'de to wrath, the queens high maiestie</l>

<l>Wo <note n="*" place="margin">Where Rorie bid the three cur<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>ses light vpon him, I wish hym for euery one twentie (sauyng my charitie.)</note>maie I be, for mouyng her to Ire,</l>
<l>The M. woes, through which my soule possesse</l>
<l>In eche respect, surpasse the flames of fire,</l>
<l>I languishe still, but hopelesse of redresse:</l>
<l>My wicked life, I needes must now confesse,</l>
<l>Through which I feele, eue<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g> liue y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> pa<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>ges of hell,</l>

<note n="*" place="margin">A good note for Rebelles, Marks the effecte, of rebellion, and wherevnto it driueth this wretched Roge, euen to the brincke of desperation, who as he saieth beyng yet aliue, feeleth moste appa<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>rantly the tormentes of hell, and here it is proued true, that a mans owne conscience is better then a thousande witnesses.</note>That neither penne, nor tongue of man can tell.</l>

<l>I am expelde,<note place="margin">There be two sortes of people on earth, knaues and honest men, whereon I ga<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ther that Rorie Ogge being ba<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>nished the com<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>panie of honest men, must be en<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tertained of his like e<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap>uall com<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>panio<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>s, (who as him self saith) is daily pursued of the good in moste wofull sorte.</note> from crewe of honest men,</l>
<l>None but my mates, me traitour maie abide,</l>
<l>As for the good, thei hunte me now and then,</l>
<l>From wooddes to Boggs, beset on eurie side:</l>
<l>And where that I, so euer am espide,</l>
<l>There waight is laied, to catche my sillie soule,</l>
<l>And with the axe, to shorte me by the poule.</l>
<l>Whiche thyng to taste, I well deserued haue,</l>
<note n="*" place="margin">Rorie is here <gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 word">

</gap> very penitent persone, whiche co<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>fesseth his life to haue deserued death, which re<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>fused the princes pardone once offered hym.</note>Since freedome once, was offerde vnto me,</l>
<l>Vaine is the gift, that's profferde to a knaue,</l>
<l>O Rebell cause, of all thy miserie,</l>
<l>Which mightest haue had, remission of thy sinne,</l>
<l>What, greater gaine, supposedst thou to winne.</l>

<note n="*" place="margin">Here Rorie Ogge taketh on with himself for refusing the par<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>done, & acknow<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ledgeth hym self an asse, and a beast in deniyng the same.</note>O dismalle daie, wherein I it denide,</l>
<l>O peruerse harte, that couldste not it imbrace,</l>
<l>But like a theef, suche courtesie denide:</l>
<l>O brutishe beast, who doeth not now deride,</l>
<l>Whose haughtie thoughts, did match y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> rouling skye.</l>
<l>But true it is, that Fatall letters saie,</l>
<l>Who takes no tyme,<note place="margin">Rorie calleth to memorie the sa<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ing that is writ<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ten, tyme beyng once past, is not easely cald back, whereby we are lea<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="2 letters">
</gap>ed to take the tyme present whilst it is of<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="2 letters">
<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>red.</note> when as the same is lent,</l>
<l>And holde it faste, hym self thereby to staie,</l>
<l>Whom if it passe, the crooked waie it went:</l>
<l>He maie not finde, the Tauerne, House or tent,</l>
<l>Though them to seeke, he spendeth daie & night</l>
<l>And all because, he helde not when he might.</l>

<note place="margin">He verifieth and approueth the aboue saiyng by hym self, whiche reiectyng grace beyng offered, now seeketh af<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ter it, but maie not haue it, though with weeping he doth request it.</note>Euen so alas, when noble <hi>Sidney</hi> he,</l>
<l>My pardon sent, for faltes I did comit,</l>
<l>Though there I saw, eche crime forgiuen to be,</l>
<l>I not contente, with chat his pardon yet:</l>
<l>Let passe the same, as gifte for me vnfit,</l>
<l>Whiche to reuert, now lyes not in my might,</l>
<l>For God & time, haue wrought me this dispight</l>

<note n="*" place="margin">Rorie Ogge sheweth for par<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>done, but maie not obtaine it, for Princes by Rebels will not be deluded.</note>Now do I seke, though sekyng nought preuaile</l>
<l>Faine would I finde, the fauour of my Prince,</l>
<l>But craft serues not, that stately forte to scaile,</l>
<l>For well she knowes, my subtill hartes pretence</l>
<l>Who hath a tyme, the same to recompence,</l>
<l>As semeth good, vnto her royall grace.</l>

<l>For God and tyme,<note n="*" place="margin">Rorie Ogg se<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>yng hym self en<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>uironed on eue<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ry side with ene<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>mies, manife<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>steth his miserie, showing not one craftie hose or <gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">

</gap>enne to be free from the know<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ledge of y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> Lord deputie, but that he hath intelli<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ge<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>ce and know<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ledge of it.</note> bid Iustice to take place.</l>
<l>And Iustice she, sendes forthe her warlike crew,</l>
<l>With sondrie spies, my haunte for to disclose,</l>
<l>Who connyngly poore Rories tracte doe vewe,</l>
<l>As nought is lefte, wherein he maie repose,</l>
<l>Mo<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>gest all his de<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>nes a bulwarke for his health</l>
<l>Nor yet a ho<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">

<note n="*" place="margin">Rorie sheweth how spitefull greedie, the En<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>glish Captanes and Souldiers are in chasyng and hu<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>ting him.</note>Like greedie haukes, pursuyng faste their praie,</l>
<l>All fullie bent, the same for to deuoure,</l>
<l>And as the Night, the Orientall daie,</l>
<l>Doeth captiue make, by his externall powre:</l>
<l>So time from time, small distance fro<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g> an howre,</l>
<l>Pursude I am<g ref="char:punc">▪</g> and brought to suche a baie,</l>
<l>As I expecte, nought but my dismall daie.</l>

<l>Sir Henry now,<note place="margin">Rorie acknow<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ledgeth y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> Lorde Deputies nota<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ble wisedome, onely to haue brought hym to this miserie.</note> who gouernes Irishe soyle,</l>
<l>Hath made an othe, to breuiate my daies,</l>
<l>Whose stratagemes, haue giuen me suche a foile</l>
<l>As all the lande, soundes out his noble praise:</l>
<l>For he it is, that breaketh doune my staies,</l>
<l>And who but he might Rorie ouerthrowe,</l>
<l>Though <hi>Mars</hi> hmself, had sworne my mortal fo.</l>
<l>Who might haue tane,<note place="margin">He proueth his affirmation by a moste manifest example, whiche was brought at that time to pas</note> out of my bloodie hande,</l>
<l>Whom by my sleightes, I captiue made to bee,</l>
<l>That Marshall knight, and captain of a bande,</l>
<l>In fine twas he, whiche made of bondmen free,</l>
<l>And put to sworde,<note place="margin">Rorie Oges wife is slaine.</note> for my vnstable truthe,</l>
<l>My spoused wife, the garlande of my youth.</l>
<l>With many mo, my deare and speciall frends,<note n="*" place="margin">Rories frend<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">

</gap>s to the nomber of sixtene are saine in a cabbin, be<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>yng in a Wood of the Englishe men, and after warde the cab<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>bin beyng set on fire, all their bo<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>dies are burned also.</note>
<l>Whose brethlesse corps, wer giue<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g> to flams of fire</l>
<l>Good cause had I, to waile their lucklesse ends,</l>
<l>Though <hi>Ioue</hi> agreed, to yeeld them suche a hire:</l>
<l>O heauie plague, to moue the heauens to Ire,</l>
<l>Through whose outrage, y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> iust oft su<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
<l>To cause the reste, from wicked actes refraine.</l>
<l>And I my self, in daunger of my life,</l>

<l>Rounde compaste then,<note n="*" place="margin">Rorie Ogg be<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>yng at that tyme in the foresaied cabbin, with those that were killed hardly es<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>capeth, though not without a good knocke of a halbert vpon his costarde.</note> by men of worthie fame,</l>
<l>Sought out to shift, how to escape the knife:</l>
<l>That readie was, my courage for to tame,</l>
<l>Whiche when that I, well pondred had thesame</l>
<l>I tooke good harte, it stoode me then vpon,</l>
<l>And leapt me forthe, tyme wilde I should be go<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>.</l>
<note place="margin">To leape well is very necessa<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>rie sometyme, as appeareth here by Rorie Ogge.</note>Now with that leape, I got me quight awaie</l>
<l>Moste ioyous that, I skaped had the trappe,</l>
<l>My leggs were good, to vow that thing I maie</l>
<l>Whiche set me free, that tide from that mishappe</l>
<l>Not ouer free, for one gaue me a rappe,</l>
<l>Whiche thing I sweare, did pinche me to y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> hart,</l>
<l>The blowe was greate, & came so ouerthwart.</l>

<note place="margin">Rorie here sho<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>weth that the Englishe men, were very sory for his escape out of the cab<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>bin, and from their handes. This happines is to be referred to the Englishe men, whose chaunce was to kill those rebel<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>lious knaues. Rorie Ogge es<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>pecially doth be waile the death of one S<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap>aue Macke Rorie Reagh aboue y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> rest that were slaine at y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> tyme.</note>But scape I did, so muche the more their greef,</l>
<l>And got me soone, into an other denne,</l>
<l>None fledde with me, but one poore onely theef,</l>
<l>As for the reste, thei were saluted then,</l>
<l>That instant tyme, were xvi. of my men,</l>
<l>Put to the sworde, in cabbande where wee laie,</l>
<l>O my ill happe, but happie theirs I saie.</l>
<l>Emongest them all, one auncient aged sire,</l>
<l>Whose councels I, eche while did well alowe,</l>
<l>Though old he was, yet pearcyng as the fire,</l>
<l>A craftie Foxe, as any liueth now:</l>
<l>Was murdered then, by chance I wot not how</l>
<l>Whose crewell fall, giuen by the sisters three,</l>
<note place="margin">Here he setteth out y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> cause why he so <gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap>eploreth his destenie.</note>For whilste he liu'de, my harte possest his lust,</l>
<l>And lust enioyde, what so it could inuent:</l>
<l>But since the poste, whereon my hope did trust,</l>
<l>Receu'de his dome, by warriours fearce assent,</l>
</gap>domes slaue, I sithens haue been pe<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>t.</l>
<note place="margin">Rorie Ogge be<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ing be reaued of his counsellers, is all moste out of his wittes.</note>In easlesse holde, not wittyng what to doe,</l>
<l>Or what were beste, to put my self vnto.</l>

<l>My men wer slain,<note place="margin">When Rebels lacke fawterers and helpers, the<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g> fall they to mi<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>serie.</note> which onely wer my staie,</l>
<l>My wife through whom, I often gat releef,</l>
<l>My fre<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>des which brought, to Rorie daie by daie</l>
<l>The stolen horse, the Mutton and the Beef,</l>
<l>Which thinges to wa<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>t, who holds it not a greef?</l>
<l>Yea suche a plague, as aucthours tell to me,</l>
<l>That to a man, no greater plague can be.</l>
<l>Loe first the woe,<note place="margin">The first steppe to Rories mise<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>rie.</note> my soule doeth ouer quell,</l>
<l>Behold y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> straight, whereto I now am brought,</l>
<l>Marke well the place, where caitife I do dwell,</l>
<l>As eke the knight, this alteration wrought,</l>
<l>Then shall you se, if throughly you haue sought</l>
<l>The perfect waie, that leadeth to the hall:</l>
<l>Where are the plagues, on Rorie Ogge shall fal.</l>

<l>For <hi>Sidney</hi> now,<note place="margin">The Lord De<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>putie is in ar<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>mour against Rorie Ogge, whose fame is spread vniuer<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>saly through out the Realme of Irelande.</note> that thrice (renowmed knight,)</l>
<l>T'augment the fame, and seruice of his (queene)</l>
<l>Stands out in feeld, by sworde to trie her right:</l>
<l>(Whose valiant hart, like to the Laurell greene,</l>
<l>For courage stoute, and prudence mixt betwene,</l>
<l>Is had in Price) renowmed for the same,</l>
<l>Through Irishe soile, w<hi rend="sup">t</hi> trompe of happie fame</l>

<l>He sondrie waies,<note place="margin">Sir Henry Sid<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>ney encreaseth Rorie Oges miserie, and wor<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>keth his subuer<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sion by his no<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>table industerie.</note> doeth aggrauate my smart,</l>
<l>He he I saie, hath wrought me sore anoye,</l>
<l>His wisedomes skill, hath dau<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>ted sore my hart:</l>
<l>He daie from daie, his accious doeth imploye,</l>
<l>False Rories daies, to breuiate with speede:</l>
<l>Because that he, so vile a life doe leede.</l>
Souldiers are sent out to put in practise, the Lord Deputies purpose.

Rorie plaieth the Astronomer this starre was sene from Dublin south west, by whiche blasyng starre, Rorie Oge coniectures his speedy fall, whiche accordyngly hapned. By these enis and cees, are ment the Mores and Comores Rories cheefe frendes.
</note>His Marshall knightes, & expert men of warre,</l>
<l>By hym are sent, to put the same in vre,</l>
<l>Who me of all, my freedome doe debarre:</l>
<l>Whereby I maie, not long their force endure,</l>
<l>But force no force, since I did so procure.</l>
<l>Bothe heauen and yearth, to be my mortall foe:</l>
<l>If in their rage, thei Rorie ouerthrowe.</l>
<l>Beholde a Starre, apparant in the Weste,</l>
<note n="*" place="margin">This H. doeth signifie, how Macke Shaue whiche is Rorie Oges father in lawe.</note>Whose fierie streames, I finde by learned skill,</l>
<l>When M Ms & Cs, to serue false Rories will,</l>
<l>Debarde shalbe, for thereof come the ill.</l>
<l>Or if that H. had seru'de his Queene a right,</l>
<l>Long sithens R. had been extirped quight.</l>

<note place="margin">This is a true and good co<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>fes<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sion of Rorie Oge, vttered in his extremitie. Rorie Oge is in his similitudes vp to the harde eares, prouyng with manifest arguments, vn<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>lesse he had been bolstered vp by his saide father in lawe and his frendes, it had been vnpossible that he should haue continued so long vnexe<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>cuted or taken.</note>When H. doth well, to deale with double hande</l>
<l>Els from his kinde, he should degenerate.</l>
<l>But if that S. his sleight did vnderstande,</l>
<l>H. should be turnde, augmenter of debate,</l>
<l>In little space, vnto a vi<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
<l>*Though yet not spide, he goeth vncorrected:</l>
<l>Whiche is the botche, wherewith R. is infected.</l>
<l>*Like as that house, whereon hym self to staie,</l>
<l>Hath sondrie postes, by workmen fastned sure,</l>
<l>With eurie puffe, maie not be blowne awaie:</l>
<l>So long as thei<g ref="char:punc">▪</g> in linked state endure,</l>
<l>Euen so my self, I doe you all assure,</l>
<l>Shall scarce betrapt w<hi rend="sup">t</hi> Fortunes fatall chau<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>ce</l>
<l>Whilst frendes w<hi rend="sup">t</hi> aide, my mischeef do aduau<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>ce.</l>
<l>But postes remou'de, the house sone hath a fall,</l>
<l>And buildyng goeth,<note place="margin">Marke here Ro<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>ries reasone, whiche speaketh by experience.</note> with violence to wracke,</l>
<l>No parte maie stande, the rofe nor yet the wall:</l>
<l>When as the same, his vnderstaies doeth lacke,</l>
<l>Euen so my self, nowhit could holde out tacke.</l>
<l>By hym or them, that seme frends to the queene.</l>
<l>Whiche if thei were,<note place="margin">Gods blessyng haste thou good Rorie for spea<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>kyng the truthe.</note> fro<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g> Rorie once remou'de,</l>
<l>Who would misdoubt, y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> peace that should ensue</l>
<l>This by his like, the wise hath often prou'de:</l>
<l>As now by me, it maie bee holden true,</l>
<l>If that the cause,<note place="margin">Rorie Ogge ta<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>keth vpon hym here, to haue skill in Phisick.</note> whereon the Phistoll grewe,</l>
<l>Had first been tane, from pacient cleane awaie:</l>
<l>No Phistoll then had sprouted there I saie.</l>

<l>But as a part,<note place="margin">As the Lorde Deputie abbrid<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>ged the daies of some of Rorie Oges fosterers in this his visi<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tation, so he pro<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>phesteth of the ende of the rest of his said fren<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>des together with hym self.</note> is silde through fatall chaunce,</l>
<l>Or by the sleight, of <hi>Sidneys</hi> prudent skill,</l>
<l>So in good tyme, the rest shall trace that dau<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>ce:</l>
<l>Whiche hetherto, haue seru'de my wicked will,</l>
<l>And since that thei, haue nourst me in myne ill.</l>
<l>Thei shall receiue, with me for their rewarde:</l>

<l>That tyme drawes nye,<note n="*" place="margin">Rorie seeth by some secret waie that his prophe<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sie is at hande, ready to be per<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>formed, and so muche the more he is certaine of it, because he doeth see Sir Henry Sidney bent wholy to his destruction.</note> and howre is at hande,</l>
<l>In whiche the cept, of my rebellyng race,</l>
<l>Shall be extirpt, and bolishte cleane the lande:</l>
<l>(For God hym self, doe sitte in iudgement place)</l>
<l>To Iudge I saie, with Iustice now the case.</l>
<l>Whiche tyme from tyme, hath euer been defard:</l>
<l>So that the right, at no tyme could bee heard.</l>
<note place="margin">Rorie Ogge t<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">

<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>keth this sithe to be the sworde of Iustice, which the Lord Depu<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tie hath plucked out of the sheath onely to do exe<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>cution vpon all transgressors.</note>Lo lo I see, in Mowers crewell hande,</l>
<l>Both here & there, throughout this Irishe lande</l>
<l>That growth of things, are at their ripned state</l>
<l>Whiche must be cropt, by Sithe of dismall fate.</l>
<l>For God and tyme, hath sworne by sacred othe:</l>
<l>That Reede & huske, shall suffer penance bothe.</l>
<l>It is at hande, for feelds declare the same,</l>
<l>The date is out, and tyme appointed spent,</l>
<l>And reapman now, the vanter to reclame:</l>
<note place="margin">The Harolde of death is sent to Rorie Oge, cer<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tainly to make manifest, his ruine and fall.</note>In Irefull rage, from mightie <hi>Ioue</hi> is sent,</l>
<l>Whose message thus, vnto me doeth present.</l>
<l>And his supporters, to suffer like destruction.</l>
<l>Then men shall walke, vpon the mou<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>taines hie,</l>
<note place="margin">The peace is discribed that shall be after the death of Ro<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>rie Oge.</note>And feare nowhit, the Tyger, Wolfe, nor Beare</l>
<l>The Kids shall slepe, with Leopard quietly:</l>
<l>And yet nowhit, his fearfull visage feare,</l>
<l>For why? no cause, of tremblyng shall be there.</l>
<l>When as the thing, whereof thei were afraied:</l>
<l>Shall be by sworde, and crewell conquest laied.</l>

<note place="margin">The Lord De<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>putie in prosecu<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ting his purpose against Rorie Oge, & through procurement of the saide Rories fall, deserueth e<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>uerlastyng re<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>membraunce, with all good & famous men.</note>The<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>
<hi>H.</hi> & <hi>S.</hi> through who<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g> this peace doth spring,</l>
<l>For his desartes, shall crouned sitte with Fame,</l>
<l>And ouer that, whiche is a better thyng:</l>
<l>Emongest the iuste, that well deserue the same.</l>
<l>And though y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> tyme, shall turne his corps to clay</l>
<l>Yet shall his name, still florishe as the Baye.</l>

<l>Lo you that liue,<note place="margin">Rorie Oge ma<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>keth here his conclusion, and giueth forthe a good exhortatio<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g> to all men, coun<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>celyng them to eschewe and flee treasons, and showeth though sinnes be for a while let go vn<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>punished, yet at length they are recompensed at full.</note> and I that soone shall dye,</l>
<l>Beholde I saie, the salerie for synne,</l>
<l>Now let my cause, teache other impes to flye:</l>
<l>From treasons lure, lest stipende like thei winne,</l>
<l>For though tis long, ere Iustice cometh in.</l>
<l>Yet when it comes, it paieth once for all:</l>
<l>And suffreth plages, by heapes on plages to fall.</l>

<seg rend="decorInit">E</seg>Nteryng into the discourse of Rorie Ogge, at the firste, I was purposely bent, frendly with hym to adioine the liues of many (the open professed enemies of her Maiesties gouerment within this Realme of Ire<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>lande) but before I had ended that portion (euen in the middest thereof) I behelde many impedi<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>mentes, wonderfull obstacklesse, stoppes, and staies perswadyng the contrarie, whiche beeyng repleni<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>shed with sufficient matter, grounded vpon rea<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>son, wisedome aduised me, to co<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>sider thereof (least peraduenture) ranging on rashely, I might seeme to prosecute an endlesse worke, making a volume, more greater, then gratefull, and more painfull, then pleasaunt, (whiche thyng doubtlesse) I vt<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>terlie abhorre. Seeyng that praise consistes not, in the quantitie, but rather, in the qualitie <gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap> grace of a thing doen. And thus I breuiated my former entent, though in effect, nothing deminishyng that whiche I promised. For in this discourse, you may

perfectly se, as in a glasse, perceiue, learne, and vn<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>derstande, to what vexations of minde, troubles of bodie, anguishe and wretchednesse in conscience all the rable of Rebels are captiued vnto. VVher<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>fore leauyng theim with their vngracious Pa<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>trones; Phisniognamies, externall; and infernall, to thy consideration (gentill Reader:) It came then into my minde, freshely to gather my wittes together, to the settyng forthe of an other maner of thyng, of greater valure then as yet thou hast seen (that is to saie) the commyng in of O Neale to (Sir Henry Sidney our Lorde Deputie of Ire<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>land) at the Newrie, with his submission, the othe that the saied O Neale the<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g> and there made, tou<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>chyng his perpetuall fidelitie, and inuiolable con<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tinuaunce of his duetifull aledgaunce, to the (que<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>nes Maiestie her royall Croune and dignitie) with sondrie other promisses moe, decently becom<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>myng euery good Subiecte: not barely in woordes to saie, but actually in deedes to accomplishe and performe, whiche if I had passed ouer in silence, some perhapps would haue blamed me of parciali<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ties, who in this Image so sharply enueighyng, a<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>gainst the wickednesse & rudenesse of woodkarne,

should haue omitted suche a presidente of humble submission, wherefore beholde the saied O Neale here making his submission, as before is saied, whō the Lord Deputie in the (Queenes Maiesties) behalf moste noblie accepteth, renderyng such honour as to his persone appertaineth. The effecte whereof hereafter followeth.

<l>IF sillie beastes,<note place="margin">If beastes whiche haue no vnderstan<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>dyng, doe re<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ioyce at win<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ters depar<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tyng, and at the comming in of sommer, (the encrea<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ser of their delightes) much more ought that man, who beyng long without the princes fauour, and kept in disgrace, be trebble ioyous, (receiued at length to mercie and fauour)</note> long pent in droopyng stale,</l>
<l>Or if the Harte, sore pincht with chillyng cold,</l>
<l>No meruaile ioyes, to see the Sommer fale,</l>
<l>Through whiche the plantes, kept doune in massie hold</l>
<l>Their fragra<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>t se<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>tes, & beauties maie vnfold.</l>
<l>Or if the Larcke, when cloudes are paste awaye,</l>
<hi>Te deum</hi> synges, to see the Sunnie daie.</l>
<l>Why should not man, the highest firmament,</l>
<l>Whose thoughtes did pearce, where <hi>Ioue</hi> resple<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>dent sit</l>
<l>Whose outward shape, the same doth represent:</l>
<l>As nexte extende, for his forecastyng witte,</l>
<l>To whom alone, he onely doeth committe.</l>
<l>The vastall worlde, with ruledome of the same:</l>
<l>The fishe in Seas, and beastes on lande to tame.</l>
<l>Reioyce I saie, vnbounde from thousande cares,</l>
<l>From greef of minde, with sorowes ouer preste,</l>
<l>From sighing sobbs, far fetcht with trillyng teares</l>
<l>From heapes of cares, clos'de vp in pantyng breste,</l>
<l>From euery thing, that might gainsaie his reste.</l>
<l>And now in place, and steade of suche anoye:</l>
<l>To reape at full, his long expected ioye.</l>
<l>This ioye at full, I meane my Princes grace,</l>

<note place="margin">The fauour of the prince is an inesti<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>mable trea<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sure to that subiect which hath it, sur<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>mountyng <gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 word">
</gap> and preacious stones.</note>The chefest wealth, that subiectes can require,</l>
<l>A learned iudge, to soile eche doubtfull case:</l>
<l>As readiest waie whereby men maie aspire,</l>
<l>To honours seate, from youth whiche all desire.</l>
<l>And more o<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap> price, then Diamonds to be solde.</l>
<l>A tower of strength, and forte of Fortitude,</l>
<note place="margin">This setteth out most liue<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>ly in sondrie, formes and fasho<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap> what a thing the fauor and grace of our Queene is.</note>A Samson strong to riue the gates a sonder,</l>
<l>A mightie Sea, that lande from lande exclude:</l>
<l>A passyng st<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap>rne, to guide mans Shipp a right:</l>
<l>A pleasant feeld, and gardeine of delight.</l>
<l>O who can tell, expressyng eurie parte,</l>

<note place="margin">The happie estate and condition of good sub<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>iects, is with out all com<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>parisons.</note>The xceedyng ioye, that loyall Subiects winne,</l>
<l>Or who can shewe, the thrice redoundyng smarte:</l>
<l>That reachlesse liues, to rebells bringeth in,</l>
<l>Whiche make things seem, as though thade neuer bin,</l>
</gap>e of price) to honour Princes Lawes:</l>
<l>Of healthe and wealthe, the sole and onely cause.</l>

<note place="margin">In deede, I think if there were any grace at al in hym, whiche is once brought to be a subiecte, he maie not lightly be tur<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>ned to be a Rebel again.</note>Who so did taste, once of that Sugred life,</l>
<l>And reape the fruite, that spryngeth of the same,</l>
<l>Bi't wildest Karn<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
<l>Weart-Macke, or O. Macke deuil weart by name</l>
<l>I thinke if grace, did them conduct a right.</l>
<l>Theilde no exchange, though change at will thei might</l>

<l>If happe to change,<note n="*" place="margin">Truly the condition of Rebelles in Irelande is very ticklish, and their chaunces ve<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ry harde, as in this part<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap> is discribed.</note> the change for worser parte,</l>
<l>As triall tells, eche where in Irishe soile,</l>
<l>In reachlesse change, things light ouerth warte<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
<l>For though the foe, in treasons feelde domoile,</l>
<l>Yet dreades he sore, eche while to get tho foile.</l>
<l>And though for once, he passeth by the trappe:</l>
<l>Yet at the length, in pantell he shall happe.</l>

<l>Yea though their straightes,<note place="margin">A most plain and true dis<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>cription of Rebelles ti<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>meros<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
<l>Are hundred Karnes preparde at all assaies,</l>
<l>Yet eurie Rushe, their haughtie hartes doeth quell:</l>
<l>As whicly winde, their courage sore alaies,</l>
<l>Thus feare them daunt, by 1000. kinde of waies.</l>
<l>Thei feare to see, the shiu'ryng of the daie:</l>
<l>Thei feare as faste, when it is paste awaie.</l>

<l>Thus feare eche while,<note place="margin">Feare euery while and where, trou<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>bleth the Re<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>bell, waking, sleepyng, and at all tymes and seasons.</note> enuironth traitors minde,</l>
<l>And cares againe, to sheeld them from mischance,</l>
<l>Thei are disturbde, at eurie puffe of winde:</l>
<l>The dusked cloudes, which ouer them do glaunce,</l>
<l>Thei saie foreshewes, some sodaine fatall chaunce.</l>
<l>And often tymes, the shaddowe of a tree:</l>
<l>Makes them beleeue, a bande of men to see.</l>

<l>Suche feare turmoiles,<note place="margin">The traiter that thinketh hym self in moste securi<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tie, is often tymes brought into greatest per<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>plexitie, such an horrible thing is trea<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sone.</note> the sturdest of them all,</l>
<l>Suche feare I saie, eche Rebell doeth retaine,</l>
<l>Suche feare I vowe, vpon the beste doeth fall:</l>
<l>Suche feare I sweare, the chefest foe doeth paine,</l>
<l>Suche feare againe, in loftest harte remaine.</l>
<l>And though suche feare, doeth ouerwhelme their hartes,</l>
<l>Yet cease thei not, to plaie disloiall partes.</l>
</gap> very foolish plaie and pa<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>styme, and moste foolish is he, that f<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="2 letters">
</gap>eth his hart and stomack with treason as if it were with moste holsome meat</note>Suche plaie maie well, be counted fooles game,</l>
<l>For none but fooles, therein doe take delight,</l>
<l>Iuste was the cause, whereof it helde the name:</l>
<l>As eke a curste, that brought it first to light,</l>
<l>In steade of foode, to glutte mans appetite.</l>
<l>And bande are all, in Citie, Feeld or Toune:</l>
<l>That holde suche plaie, against the royall croune.</l>
<note place="margin">Those that liue well, and loue well their Prince, is euery wher counted hap<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>pie & blessed.</note>But bleste are thei, that doe refuse the same,</l>
<l>And trebble blest, that loue their Prince a right,</l>
<l>Blest shall he bee, whiche pretermittes that game:</l>
<l>Yea bleste I saie, bothe mornyng and at night,</l>
<l>Bleste shall he bee, whiche hath his whole delight.</l>
<l>In good attemptes, and furdryng Princ's cause:</l>
<l>Conductyng hym, by tenour of her Lawes.</l>
<note place="margin">This is the protestation of O Neale to the Lorde Deputie.</note>My Princes freende, I vowe my self to bee,</l>
<l>And loyall eke, vnto her noble grace,</l>
<l>A freende to her, a freende likewise to me:</l>
<l>As tyme shall trie, the vtmoste of her case,</l>
<l>And who that seekes, her honour to deface.</l>
<l>I doe protest, by all my force and might:</l>
<l>My blood to gage, but Ile maintaine her right.</l>
<note place="margin">This is largely prof<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ferd of hym.</note>In Princes cause, my hande shall strike y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> stroke,</l>
<l>And who that dare, her Cepter to defame,</l>
<l>As he that will, not yet againe reuoke:</l>
<l>By Marshall actes, that persone Ile reclame,</l>
<l>And make hym yeeld, submission to her name.</l>
<l>Yea though he were, a seconde <hi>Mars</hi> I vowe:</l>
<l>Ile make hym stoope, to breake, to bende, or bowe.</l>
<l>Fewe Scottes in North (if Quene will haue it so)</l>

<l>Shall there abide,<note place="margin">O Neale pro<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>miseth to ex<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>pell al Scots out of the North of Irelande, if the Queenes Maiestie would but giue hym ayde, or if her grace would haue it so.</note> the grounde for to manure,</l>
<l>Excepte that thei, their homage yeeld her to:</l>
<l>Not one I saie (if Queene will me supporte)</l>
<l>Shall there possesse, one castell toune or forte.</l>
<l>Since I haue reapte, the thyng I did desire,</l>
<l>And wonne at laste, the fauour of the croune,</l>
<l>My harte is set, as twere in flames of fire:</l>
<l>By seruice iuste,<note place="margin">Meanyng Sir Henry Sidney, to whom O Neale made like protesta<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tion.</note> t'augmene her greate renowne,</l>
<l>Whiche shall appeare, by Rebells pluckyng doune.</l>
<l>Withstandyng the<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>, that shall withstande her right:</l>
<l>In midste of feelde, (I vow'de it to her knight.)</l>
<l>Let them beware,<note place="margin">An admoni<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tion to the enhabitantes and borde<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>rers neare to the North</note> that border nere my holde,</l>
<l>In any case<g ref="char:punc">▪</g> how thei their liues doe leede,</l>
<l>For with an othe, to vowe I maie be bolde:</l>
<l>If to their cuttes, thei take not better heede,</l>
<l>In harte and minde, I fullie am agreed.</l>

<l>The beste to quell,<note place="margin">O Neale pro<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>miseth not onely to be a scourdge to the euill li<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>uers and di<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sturbers of her Maie<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sties people, but also a frende and helper of her good sub<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>iectes to the vttermost of his powre.</note> (that shall molest her grace:)</l>
<l>Demissyng them, from honour, life, and place.</l>
<l>But *those that leade, a faithfull subiectes life,</l>
<l>I their defence, doe put my self to bee,</l>
<l>Supportyng them, in eurie kinde of strife:</l>
<l>By waie I saie, of noble cheualrie.</l>
<l>And whereas I, maie doe them any good:</l>
<l>For Princes sake, Ile hazarde life and blood.</l>
<l>Come eche wight, whiche now do haunt the wood,</l>
<l>Submit your selues, vnto your soueraignes lawe,</l>
<l>Come forthe I saie, receiue my councell good:</l>
<l>Let not fonde luste, your sences thence withdrawe,</l>
<l>But of the croune, like subiectes stande in awe.</l>
<l>So shall you finde, suche fauour of the Queene:</l>
<l>As hetherto, the like you haue not scene.</l>
<l>In steade of woodes, then houses you maie vse,</l>
<l>In steade of Boggs, the Cities at your will,</l>
<l>Procede therefore, leste tyme you should abuse:</l>
<l>Now reape the fruite, of pleasure euen your fill.</l>
<l>(In fine) submit, you (to her royall grace:</l>
<l>So mercie shall, areste you with her Mace.</l>

<seg rend="decorInit">T</seg>HE miserable calamitie of Rorie Ogge set out by meanes of the dead<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ly pursute of valiaunt seruitures daily pursewyng him, remained no<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>thyng to the concludyng of my la<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>bours, but the finall endyng of his wretched race, which thing I constantly beleued would shortly come to passe, (admirable both to the beholders and seers) for as his life was notorious and passyng knauishe, so could it not otherwise be, but that his death must a<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>gree, fallyng out equall in eache condition to his trai<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>terous vsage, for seldome is it seen, that wicked re<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>belling hath a blessed ending, and as men oftentymes hope not in vaine, so I expectyng, or rather wishing, the cuttyng of (of suche a botchie member (receiued at length, the rewarde of my expectation, in the ful<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>nesse of the thyng I so long thursted for. (For as God would) it came luckely to passe, (long tyme predesti<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>nated by his vnsearchable and secret counsell) efte sone, as I had ended with the discription of O Neale, that this cursed caitife, (cursed of gods own mouth)

was through the sworde, by the meanes of the Lorde of Vppossery and his seruiters (a faithfull subiecte of that Realme) bereaued of his life, to the greate tranquilitie of Lease, and els where (her Maiesties leage people there inhabityng) accordyng to the true prophesie, in his liuyng story, at large set out. VVherfore, and for as muche, as I suppose your desire is, to heare some discourse consernyng his death, as you heard before touchyng his life, suppose that you see a monstrous Deuill, a trunckelesse head, and a hedlesse bodie liuyng, the one hid in some miskin & donghill, but the other exalted, yea mounted vppon a poule (a proper sight God wot to be holde (vanting it self on the highest toppe of the Castell of Dublin, vtteryng in plaine Irishe the thynges that ensewe.

<l>WHilste feare ioynde w<hi rend="sup">t</hi> hope,<note place="margin">In this part Rorie Oge showeth the state of that man to be sure, so long as he kepeth hym self du<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tifull to his Prince and Countrie.</note> liege people retaine,</l>
<l>A feare to offende, the Prince or her lawe,</l>
<l>And hope for desartes, suche goodnesse to gaine:</l>
<l>As shall be imposde, to the line they drawe,</l>
<l>Whilste one vprightly, twixt these standes in awe.</l>
<l>He dreades no turbulent stormes that maie chau<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>ce</l>
<l>For tyme trieth falshood, the trothe to aduaunce.</l>
<l>But feare expulsed, clene out of the mynde,</l>
<l>Not waiyng Iustice,<note place="margin">That man whiche ca<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>steth of feare falleth into many mis<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>chefes.</note> detectour of sinne:</l>
<l>And hope of correction, which subiectes doth binde,</l>
<l>Their liues for to leade, the statutes within,</l>
<l>To plaie her pagent, as wily she can:</l>
<l>She spoyleth wholy, the nature of man.</l>

<l>Procuryng enuie,<note place="margin">He that hath wicked ran<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>cour in his breast, hath with it also a greate nom<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ber of euill vices. Tyme is a detectour of treasone.</note> grudge, strife, and debate,</l>
<l>Anger, and malice, bothe fit for the turne,</l>
<l>Holdyng them smouldryng, and neuer to burne,</l>
<l>Till tyme descries it, detectyng the treason:</l>
<l>Whiche then is maintainde, by colour of reason.</l>
<l>Aledgyng reason,<note place="margin">Treason e<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>spied, is exe<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>cused by rea<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sone.</note> suche folly to couer,</l>
<l>Though treason not reason, is chefest pretence,</l>
<l>Thus whilste in malice, the Rebell doeth houer:</l>
<pb facs="tcp:14477:48"/>Raising a powre, to be his defence,</l>
<l>To subiectes disquiet, the Realme and the Prince,</l>
<l>Good God what reason, iste then to defende,</l>
<l>The thyng that treason, is founde in the ende?</l>

<note place="margin">That traiter which is wil<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>fully giuen to plaie the Rebell, hath neuer regard to the cause be it good or bad, for whiche he riseth.</note>But man addicted, to fancie and will,</l>
<l>Forced by Sathan, to followe his luste,</l>
<l>Regardes not the cause, be it good or ill:</l>
<l>For whiche in hazarde, his life he doeth thruste,</l>
<l>He passe not a myte, b'it iust, or vniust:</l>
<l>For as the Pooke leades hym, so forward he must:</l>
<l>Not ceasing till bayarde, laith hym in the dust.</l>
<note place="margin">A Rebell doeth not re<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>member w<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap>at is the ende of his treasons.</note>He nought forcasteth, enflamed with yre,</l>
<l>At last what guerdon, false treason awarde,</l>
<l>What plagues for traitours, y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> law hath preparde,</l>
<l>To thinges before hym, or after ensewe:</l>
<l>He sone possesse, what for treasone is dewe.</l>
<note place="margin">Though for<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tune doeth fauer the traitour for a while, yet at last she leaueth hym in the bryers.</note>Although for a tyme, dame fortune doeth smile,</l>
<l>Fauryng moste frendly, the thing set abroche,</l>
<l>Whose craftie suggestions, compact in a wise,</l>
<l>At last bringes the Rebell, to shame and reproche,</l>
<l>Deludyng his rashnesse, that darde to encroche,</l>
<l>So muche on fortune, abusing her wheele:</l>
<l>That leaste puffe of winde, doeth make for to reele.</l>
<l>What here is spoken, a thousande haue tride,</l>
<l>Who maie be triall, the truth will declare,</l>
<pb facs="tcp:14477:48"/>The course of fortune,<note place="margin">Many <gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 word">
</gap> founde fo<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tune very de<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>c<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
<l>As how she seketh, but people to snare:</l>
<l>To snarle and intangle, with sorowe and care,</l>
<l>And they thus hampred, from them to flie,</l>
<l>Suffryng those captiues, in fetters to lie.</l>
<l>Yet she forsakes not,<note place="margin">To augment the mise<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">

</gap>ie of man, fortune doeth some tyme seeme frendly, rid<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>dyng him out of one small trouble, to bryng hym in to fowre greater, and then bids hym adewe.</note> still men in their neede,</l>
<l>As who that listeth, in stories to reede,</l>
<l>Shall see how frendly, she seekes their release,</l>
<l>Though for no true loue, yet more to encrease,</l>
<l>The plague of vengeaunce, that after ensewe,</l>
<l>(A stipende iustly, to traitours b'yng dewe)</l>
<l>These thinges to confirme, I Rorie am he,</l>
<l>Who sometyme mounted,<note n="*" place="margin">Rorie Oge is a sufficient witnesse, to tell of Dame Fortunes variablenes.</note> a lofte in the Skie,</l>
<l>And fortune castyng, a fauour to me:</l>
<l>Prouoked me higher, and higher to flie,</l>
<l>Thus like an Eagle, I neastled on hie,</l>
<l>Or that my glorie, would euer haue ende.</l>

<l>In all my actions,<note place="margin">Marke how fortune did fauer Rorie Oge, accor<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>dyng to his owne setyng, who beyng to muche besot<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ted therwith, fell to vtter confusion and shame at last.</note> moste happie successe,</l>
<l>For what I mynded, in harte to suppresse:</l>
<l>The same accomplisht, she caused to bee,</l>
<l>Thus will and fortune, did euer agree,</l>
<l>Whiche thing espied, puft vp with aspiraunce:</l>
<l>I stoode with Sir Henrie, alas at defiaunce.</l>
<l>Muche like a champion, addicted to warre,</l>
</gap> Oge gathereth eight score men to main<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>taine his knauerie.</note>Tyme seruyng fitly, to anger my foes,</l>
</gap>nde a nomber, of neighbours from farre:</l>
<l>Twice eightie persones, the beste I could chose,</l>
<l>For manhood, and sleightes, in whom to repose,</l>
<l>I might in saftie, my life and my lande:</l>
<l>No dasterdes nor shrincklinges, but those y<hi rend="sup">t</hi> would stande.</l>

<note place="margin">Rorie Oge troubleth both Toune and Country with his Karne, and setteth more then a hun<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>dred houses on fire in one night.</note>With these I marched, from place vnto place,</l>
<l>With these I troubled bothe Uillage and Toune,</l>
<l>With these in one night, I fired the <hi>Nace:</hi>
<l>With these my <hi>Recisters,</hi> I spoylde of renoune,</l>
<l>With these I made many a Castell come doune,</l>
<l>With these I yeelded, augmentyng my fame:</l>
<l>The people to sworde, and houses to flame.</l>
<l>With these I wasted, the Countie of <hi>Lease,</hi>
<l>The places likewise, that bordred it nye,</l>

<note place="margin">Rorie Oge maketh the Farmers of Leasse to giue ouer their plo<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>wing, by rea<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>sone of his daily robbing and burning.</note>I made from tillage, the Farmors to cease:</l>
<l>I made them gladly, awaie for to flye,</l>
<l>Inuityng them nightly, with a freshe supplye,</l>
<l>Giuyng my woodkarne, their states to maintaine</l>
<l>The fruite that growed, of other mens paine.</l>

<note place="margin">The iust Iu<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>stice of God permitteth not Rorie Oge to rage still on in his furie, but ca<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>lyng hym to accompt yeil<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>deth hym his duetie.</note>Might not of Iustice, permit me furder,</l>
<l>To rage in suche furie, delightyng in strife:</l>
<l>For my demenure, since wilfull I swarued:</l>
<l>And here I lye groulyng, poore wretch on y<hi rend="sup">e</hi> grou<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g>d</l>
<l>Spoylde of the Iewell,<note place="margin">Rorie Oge hed is sert vp<g ref="char:EOLunhyphen"/>pon the top of the Cas<gap reason="illegible" resp="#PDCC" extent="1 letter">
</gap>el of Dublin, for a specta<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>kle to all the whole lande.</note> I cheefly loued,</l>
<l>Thus God of Iustice, doeth traitours confounde:</l>
<l>When from their sinnes, thaile not be remoued,</l>
<l>With shame and confusion, I now am reproued,</l>
<l>My hed from the bodie, parted in twaine:</l>
<l>Is set on the Castell, a signe to remaine.</l>

<l>All men that heare this, take warnyng by me,<note place="margin">Rorie Oge maketh here his conclusio<g ref="char:cmbAbbrStroke">̄</g> and giueth wholsome counsel more better then he euer could take, how they attempt any thyng that might be preiudiciall to the prince, for feare of like distruc<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tion.</note>
<l>Least that ye fall, in like predicament,</l>
<l>The arte of treason, see likewise ye flee:</l>
<l>Against the Croune royall, doe nothyng attempt,</l>
<l>For if against it, ye falyng at odde:</l>
<l>Doe feele as I felt, the strength of the rodde.</l>
